  "stage": {
    "id": "course_1_fundamentals",
    "stageNumber": 1,
    "title": "Object Detection Fundamentals",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "object_detection",
        "title": "What is Object Detection?",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- multiple objects in images\n- localization and classification\n- why detection matters\n\nRedmon & Farhadi introduce YOLO v3 as a practical solution to real-world vision problems where you need to find *where* objects are, not just *what* they are. Think of it like a security camera system: you don't just want to know \"there's a person in this image,\" you want to know \"there's a person at coordinates (150, 200) in a 50×60 box.\"\n\nThis is fundamentally different from image classification, where a single label covers the entire image. Detection requires spatial awareness — predicting locations for multiple objects simultaneously.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "bounding_boxes",
        "title": "Representing Objects with Bounding Boxes",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- rectangle representation\n- coordinate encoding\n- anchor priors\n\nBounding boxes are rectangles that \"wrap\" detected objects. The simplest representation is (x1, y1, x2, y2) — top-left and bottom-right corners. YOLOv3 actually predicts (tx, ty, tw, th) — offset from the grid cell's top-left, and log-scale width/height relative to anchor priors.\n\nThink of anchors like a \"clipboard with pre-printed boxes of different sizes\" — the model predicts adjustments to these templates rather than drawing from scratch.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "conv_layers",
        "title": "Convolutional Layers: The Building Blocks",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- spatial feature extraction\n- learned filters\n- efficient computation\n\nA convolutional layer slides a small learned filter (e.g., 3×3) across the image, computing dot products at each position. This produces feature maps showing where edges, textures, and patterns appear. Stacking many conv layers creates hierarchical features: early layers detect edges, mid layers detect shapes, deep layers detect objects.\n\nDarknet-53 has 53 such layers — each one refining the feature representation. It's like asking an increasingly specific question at each layer: \"Are there edges here? Are there corners? Are there wheels?\"",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "iou_metric",
        "title": "IoU: Measuring Detection Quality",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- intersection area\n- union area\n- overlap measure\n\nIoU (Intersection over Union) = Area(Overlap) / Area(Combined). In the example: 20 / 100 = 0.2 IoU.\n\nIoU tells us: \"How well does my prediction match the ground truth?\" An IoU of 0.5 is typically considered \"hit,\" while <0.5 is \"miss.\" It's the metric used both for training (to define what counts as a good prediction) and evaluation (to score the final model).",
        "position": {
          "x": 7,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "map_metric",
        "title": "mAP: The Standard Detection Benchmark",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- average precision\n- class-wise evaluation\n- benchmark standard\n\nmAP is the gold standard metric in object detection papers. YOLOv3 claims \"28.2 mAP at 320×320 resolution.\" This means: for each object class, compute a precision-recall curve at different confidence thresholds and IoU thresholds (commonly 0.5 and 0.75), then average across classes.\n\nHigher mAP = better model. Comparing mAP across papers lets researchers know who's winning the detection race.",
        "position": {
          "x": 11,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-1",
      "question": "mAP (Mean Average Precision) evaluates detection by: What's the proper definition?",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "Summing IoU scores across all detections",
        "Averaging precision-recall curves across classes and IoU thresholds",
        "Simply counting correct predictions"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "Averaging precision-recall curves across classes and IoU thresholds",
      "position": {
        "x": 18,
        "y": 7
      }
    },
